WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.845
Cystic fibrosis is a genetic disease that
affects the lungs,

2
00:00:04.385 --> 00:00:06.844
pancreas, and other organs by producing
thick,

3
00:00:07.344 --> 00:00:09.444
sticky secretions that disrupt normal
function.

4
00:00:10.045 --> 00:00:13.885
At the core of this disease is a defective
CFTR protein,

5
00:00:14.444 --> 00:00:18.305
which normally regulates chloride and
water movement across cell membranes.

6
00:00:19.264 --> 00:00:23.985
Without proper CFTR function, secretions
become dehydrated and thick,

7
00:00:24.584 --> 00:00:27.084
leading to airway obstruction, mucus
plugging,

8
00:00:27.424 --> 00:00:28.405
and chronic infection.

9
00:00:29.245 --> 00:00:31.725
In the lungs, this creates a cycle of
obstruction,

10
00:00:32.604 --> 00:00:33.584
infection, and inflammation.

11
00:00:34.625 --> 00:00:38.665
Thick mucus traps bacteria, most notably
Pseudomonas aeruginosa,

12
00:00:39.325 --> 00:00:40.705
leading to repeated infections.

13
00:00:41.525 --> 00:00:43.564
Over time, this causes airway damage,

14
00:00:43.985 --> 00:00:46.805
bronchiectasis, and progressive decline in
lung function.

15
00:00:47.064 --> 00:00:51.625
As respiratory therapists, it's critical
to recognize that airway clearance,

16
00:00:51.985 --> 00:00:56.325
not just bronchodilation, is a primary
priority in cystic fibrosis

17
00:00:56.325 --> 00:00:56.685
care.

18
00:00:57.625 --> 00:01:00.845
Patients often present with chronic cough,
fixed butum production,

19
00:01:01.525 --> 00:01:04.805
frequent respiratory infections, and
decreased exercise tolerance.

20
00:01:05.404 --> 00:01:08.665
You may also see signs outside the lungs,
such as

21
00:01:08.665 --> 00:01:12.224
pancreatic insufficiency, malnutrition,
and failure to

22
00:01:12.224 --> 00:01:14.305
thrive, especially in pediatric patients.

23
00:01:14.425 --> 00:01:18.584
A key diagnostic test is the sweat
chloride test, where

24
00:01:18.584 --> 00:01:22.264
elevated chloride levels confirm impaired
CFTR function.

25
00:01:23.544 --> 00:01:27.025
Management focuses on improving mucus
clearance, controlling infection,

26
00:01:27.224 --> 00:01:28.224
and supporting nutrition.

27
00:01:29.224 --> 00:01:33.444
Airway clearance techniques like chest
physiotherapy, oscillatory devices,

28
00:01:33.745 --> 00:01:36.684
and high-frequency chest wall oscillation
are essential.

29
00:01:37.684 --> 00:01:41.464
Medications include bronchodilators,
mucolytics like Dornase Alpha,

30
00:01:42.144 --> 00:01:46.845
hyperatomic saline to hydrate secretions,
and inhaled antibiotics for chronic

31
00:01:46.845 --> 00:01:47.504
infections.

32
00:01:48.625 --> 00:01:55.285
CFTR modulators target the underlying
defect in select patients and can significantly improve outcomes.

33
00:01:56.105 --> 00:01:59.144
Red flags include increasing sputum,
worsening cough,

34
00:01:59.944 --> 00:02:01.584
declining oxygenation, and fatigue.

35
00:02:02.084 --> 00:02:03.904
These may signal an exacerbation.

36
00:02:04.565 --> 00:02:07.764
From an RT perspective, always assess
secretion burden,

37
00:02:08.384 --> 00:02:10.945
effectiveness of airway clearance, breath
sounds,

38
00:02:11.445 --> 00:02:13.884
oxygenation, and patient adherence to
therapy.

39
00:02:14.725 --> 00:02:18.544
The key takeaway is that cystic fibrosis
is not just an obstructive disease,

40
00:02:18.645 --> 00:02:21.264
it is a secretion and infection-driven
disease.

41
00:02:22.044 --> 00:02:26.065
Effective management depends on aggressive
airway clearance, infection control,

42
00:02:26.505 --> 00:02:28.365
and long-term multidisciplinary care.

